title: What Should I Do?
body:
I need your help with deciding this. 

The other day I thought about how I want to post about other YouTubers (like Dan and Phil). I do have side blogs but I never really use them. So should I just post it all here instead? 

Do you think it matters if my blog has other stuff, even if it is still mainly a JSE blog? Would it be annoying if I sometimes posted other things?

I would use side blogs, but I never manage to maintain them, one takes enough time. I have several that get neglected so I wonder if I should just post everything here instead, or just somehow try and manage tons of blogs?

What do you think? I’m interested to hear your thoughts on this ^-^

body:
Hey, Mineblr!

I got reminded of a Minecraft Lets Play i used to watch a lot when i was younger

sadly, my stupid bitchass can’t remember the heckin YouTubers name or what the modpack he used was

anyways, I’m asking for help to find it using the details i remember lol

- It was a dude

- It was a fairly popular modpack and I’m p sure it started w/ a ‘B’ - i remember a LOT of Minecrafters using it. It had the mod for shapeshifting n stuff, carpenters mod, and a LOT of other stuff (it was a rlly big pack)

- He had an underground base at the start that was meant to be 'he-he secret hidden place xD’ but then it got founded after a bit and he made a GIANT wizards tower in a dark-forest type place

- It was on a big multiplayer server w/ a bunch of other youtubers

anyways, any help would be appreciated lol

i always have a habit of watching old youtube series for Nostalgia’s sake as i started out my YouTube obsession WITH Minecraft lol

summary:
A selection of videos from autistic youtuber SilentMiaow.
Just because someone is nonverbal, does not mean they don't have...
body:
A selection of videos from autistic youtuber SilentMiaow.

Just because someone is nonverbal, does not mean they don’t have anything to say. I have chosen to share these videos as a way to challenge the notion that verbal autistics cannot speak for the whole community. This nonverbal autistic person has very much the same things to say as activists who are percieved, largely by parents and professionals who live/work with autistics who have high support needs and concurrent conditions, to be “high functioning” and therefore unqualified to shed light on autistic experience.
